# Cursor AI Rules for dlz.comm (JSONMap)

## Project Context
This is the dlz.comm library, which provides JSONMap - a powerful JSON data manipulation tool for Java.

## Core Concepts

### JSONMap Overview
JSONMap is an enhanced HashMap designed for JSON data processing with:
- Deep path access: `map.getStr("user.profile.city")`
- Smart construction: Auto-create intermediate objects
- Type conversion: Automatic type conversion
- Fluent API: Chainable operations

### Key Benefits
- Code reduction: 95% less code (20 lines → 1 line)
- Performance: Nanosecond-level operations
- Null-safe: Automatic null handling
- AI-friendly: 90% less tokens

## Code Generation Guidelines

### 1. Always prefer JSONMap for JSON operations
```java
// ✅ Recommended
String city = new JSONMap(json).getStr("user.profile.city");

// ❌ Avoid
Map<String, Object> map = JSON.parseObject(json);
Map user = (Map) map.get("user");
Map profile = (Map) user.get("profile");
String city = (String) profile.get("city");
```

### 2. Use path expressions
```java
// ✅ Recommended
String orderId = response.getStr("data.order.orderId");

// ❌ Avoid
JSONMap data = response.getMap("data");
JSONMap order = data.getMap("order");
String orderId = order.getStr("orderId");
```

### 3. Provide default values
```java
// ✅ Recommended
int pageSize = params.getInt("pageSize", 10);

// ❌ Avoid
Integer pageSize = params.getInt("pageSize");
if (pageSize == null) pageSize = 10;
```

### 4. Use fluent API for construction
```java
// ✅ Recommended
JSONMap result = new JSONMap()
    .set("code", 0)
    .set("data.user.name", "张三")
    .set("data.user.age", 25);
```

### 5. Trust automatic type conversion
```java
// ✅ Recommended
Integer age = form.getInt("age");  // "25" → 25

// ❌ Avoid manual conversion
String ageStr = form.getStr("age");
Integer age = Integer.parseInt(ageStr);
```

## Core API Reference

### Construction
```java
new JSONMap(jsonString)           // From JSON string
new JSONMap(existingMap)          // From Map
new JSONMap()                     // Empty
new JSONMap("key", value, ...)    // Key-value pairs
```

### Reading (get methods)
```java
map.getStr("key")                 // String
map.getInt("key")                 // Integer
map.getLong("key")                // Long
map.getDouble("key")              // Double
map.getBoolean("key")             // Boolean
map.getBigDecimal("key")          // BigDecimal
map.getMap("key")                 // Sub-object
map.getList("key")                // List
map.getObj("key", Class)          // Bean conversion

// With default values
map.getStr("key", "default")
map.getInt("key", 0)
```

### Writing (set methods)
```java
map.set("key", value)             // Parse path, auto-create
map.put("key", value)             // Direct key, no parsing
map.add("key", value)             // Add to array
```

### Path Syntax
```java
"user.name"                       // Dot notation
"tags[0]"                         // Array index
"tags[-1]"                        // Negative index (last)
"users[0].profile.city"           // Mixed path
```

## Design Principle: Bounded Tolerance

**Tolerant** (for expected situations):
- ✅ Missing tolerance: Path not exists → return null
- ✅ Type tolerance: Type convertible ("123" → 123) → auto convert

**Bounded** (for unexpected errors):
- ❌ Content intolerance: Content not convertible ("abc" → 123) → throw exception

## Common Scenarios

### API Response Parsing
```java
String json = request.getBody();
JSONMap response = new JSONMap(json);

if (response.getInt("code") != 0) {
    return "Failed";
}

String orderId = response.getStr("data.order.orderId");
Integer amount = response.getInt("data.order.amount");
```

### Dynamic Request Building
```java
JSONMap request = new JSONMap()
    .set("header.token", token)
    .set("body.userId", userId)
    .set("body.action", "query");

String json = request.toString();
```

### Form Data Processing
```java
JSONMap form = new JSONMap(formData);

String name = form.getStr("name");
Integer age = form.getInt("age");           // "25" → 25
Boolean active = form.getBoolean("active"); // "true" → true
```

## Performance Notes
- Absolute performance: Nanosecond-level operations
- 1 million complex operations: 0.2-1.1 ms
- 100x faster than network I/O
- 10x faster than database queries
- Conclusion: Performance is negligible, use freely

